<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,258,1290]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,258,283]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Forewing length of male 
<quantity box="[564,704,258,282]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.195" metricValueMax="4.59" metricValueMin="3.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="cm" value="4.195" valueMax="4.59" valueMin="3.8">3.8–4.59 cm</quantity>
(mean = 
<number box="[812,864,258,282]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="4.32">4.32</number>
, n = 
<number box="[919,934,258,282]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="5.0">5</number>
), and female 
<quantity box="[1088,1242,258,282]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.195" metricValueMax="5.42" metricValueMin="4.97" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="cm" value="5.195" valueMax="5.42" valueMin="4.97">4.97–5.42 cm</quantity>
(mean = 
<number box="[1349,1387,258,282]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="5.2">5.2</number>
, n = 
<number box="[151,168,294,318]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="2.0">2</number>
). Very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[364,458,294,319]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[364,458,294,319]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but males lack a dorsal hair pencil in the hind wing discal cell. In males and females, postmedial border of dorsal forewing orange area more jagged than in 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[942,1035,331,355]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[942,1035,331,355]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Dorsal hind wing orange area usually smaller than in 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[373,466,366,391]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[373,466,366,391]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. General ventral coloration less vivid that in 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[972,1065,366,391]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[972,1065,366,391]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(fresh specimens of both species were compared), making the ventral forewing submarginal band paler. The color of this band is brown anteriorly to charcoal posteriorly in 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[410,563,438,463]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catharinae">
<emphasis box="[410,563,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. catharinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while it is more homogeneously brown in 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[1052,1145,438,463]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[1052,1145,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Females are very similar to, and difficult to separate from, those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[636,731,475,499]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[636,731,475,499]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Female ventral forewing brown submarginal band faded and usually showing a subtle ripple pattern.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,258,1290]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,314,546,571]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Genitalia.</emphasis>
Both the male and female genitalia are similar in size those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[1030,1124,547,571]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[1030,1124,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Male valva more robust at base both in lateral and ventral views than 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[631,724,582,607]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[631,724,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(two dissections), with some variation in the subterminal valva spines (spines in 
<figureCitation box="[343,408,618,642]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1699,1722]" captionTargetBox="[202,1383,198,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[194,1388,193,1678]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Blepolenis male and female genitalia, including dissection numbers as listed in Appendix 1. Male genitalia is illustrated in lateral and ventral views (setae omitted from right side of figure to emphasize the shape), an outline of the tegumen is given in dorsal view, and outlines of the distal portion of the valva in lateral view show the variation in the dorsal, subterminal spines. The ventral view of female sterigma includes most, but not all the length of the lateral arms. All drawings in the same scale except for corpus bursa; scale bars 1 mm, appearing under A and C. A, Blepolenis bassus male, Murtinho, Paraná, 09 - 14. B, B. bassus male valvae, top figure is the left valva of the specimen in A; bottom left, Brazil, 01 - 31; bottom right, Brazil, 08 - 41. C, B. bassus female (the irregular signa are an artifact of preparation), São Bento [do Sul], [Rio Grande do Sul], 01 - 32. D, B. batea male, Serra do Caraça, Minas Gerais, 09 - 05. E, B. batea male valvae, top to bottom, left to right: Nova Friburgo, Rio de Janeiro, 01 - 33; S. Paulo, 09 - 04; Pelotas, Rio Grande do Sul, 06 - 15; Nova Teutônia, Santa Catarina, 08 - 42. F, B. batea female, Santa Catarina, 06 - 16. G, B. catharinae male, Lagoa do Peri, Florianópolis, Santa Catarina, 09 - 01. H, no data, 09 - 15. I, Lagoa do Peri, Florianópolis, Santa Catarina, 09 - 02." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/205028/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Fig. 
<number box="[394,408,618,642]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
H are rounded and flat like those in 
<taxonomicName box="[811,943,619,643]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Opsiphanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[811,943,619,643]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Opsiphanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In ventral view, the distal portion of valva seems narrower in 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[363,515,654,679]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catharinae">
<emphasis box="[363,515,654,679]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. catharinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than in 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[605,698,654,679]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[605,698,654,679]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Female sterigma with long lateral arms, main plate tall, posterior edge with a weakly sclerotized portion at midline, and midline lobe shorter than 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[1084,1180,691,715]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[1084,1180,691,715]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(one dissection only). Corpus bursa elongated, with paired signa, and broad at the meeting point with the also broad ductus bursa, which obscures the boundary between the two structures (
<figureCitation box="[724,793,762,786]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1699,1722]" captionTargetBox="[202,1383,198,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[194,1388,193,1678]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Blepolenis male and female genitalia, including dissection numbers as listed in Appendix 1. Male genitalia is illustrated in lateral and ventral views (setae omitted from right side of figure to emphasize the shape), an outline of the tegumen is given in dorsal view, and outlines of the distal portion of the valva in lateral view show the variation in the dorsal, subterminal spines. The ventral view of female sterigma includes most, but not all the length of the lateral arms. All drawings in the same scale except for corpus bursa; scale bars 1 mm, appearing under A and C. A, Blepolenis bassus male, Murtinho, Paraná, 09 - 14. B, B. bassus male valvae, top figure is the left valva of the specimen in A; bottom left, Brazil, 01 - 31; bottom right, Brazil, 08 - 41. C, B. bassus female (the irregular signa are an artifact of preparation), São Bento [do Sul], [Rio Grande do Sul], 01 - 32. D, B. batea male, Serra do Caraça, Minas Gerais, 09 - 05. E, B. batea male valvae, top to bottom, left to right: Nova Friburgo, Rio de Janeiro, 01 - 33; S. Paulo, 09 - 04; Pelotas, Rio Grande do Sul, 06 - 15; Nova Teutônia, Santa Catarina, 08 - 42. F, B. batea female, Santa Catarina, 06 - 16. G, B. catharinae male, Lagoa do Peri, Florianópolis, Santa Catarina, 09 - 01. H, no data, 09 - 15. I, Lagoa do Peri, Florianópolis, Santa Catarina, 09 - 02." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/205028/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Fig. 
<number box="[777,793,762,786]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="2.0">
<date box="[777,793,762,786]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">2</date>
</number>
</figureCitation>
I).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,898,798,823]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,258,1290]" box="[197,898,798,823]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,798,823]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[357,428,798,822]" name="Brazil" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, Atlantic forest, Paraná to Santa Catarina.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,258,1290]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,499,834,859]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Variation and subspecies.</emphasis>
The only described subspecies (
<taxonomicName authority="Stichel, 1925" authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1925" box="[861,1333,834,859]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="catharinae" subSpecies="berchmansi">
<emphasis box="[861,1149,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. catharinae berchmansi</emphasis>
(Stichel, 
<number box="[1256,1314,834,858]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1925.0">1925</number>
))
</taxonomicName>
, and also a ‘variety’ and an ‘aberration’ were synonymized by 
<bibRefCitation author="Casagrande" box="[748,964,870,894]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refString="Casagrande, M. M. (2004) Brassolini. p. 201 - 205. In: J. B. Heppner (ed.). Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera. Part 4 A Checklist (ed. by G. Lamas). Association of Tropical Lepidoptera / Scientific publishers, Gainesville. 439 p." type="book chapter" year="2004">
Casagrande (
<number box="[894,956,870,894]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="2004.0">2004</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[1025,1073,871,895]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">type</typeStatus>
locality for this species is Santa Catarina state, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Fruhstorfer" box="[365,573,906,930]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refString="Fruhstorfer, H. (1912) 5. Familie: Brassolidae. p. 285 - 328. In: Seitz, A. (ed.), Die Gross-Schmetterlinge der Erde. Stuttgart, volume 5. Alfred Kernen." type="book chapter" year="1912">
Fruhstorfer (
<number box="[506,564,906,930]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1912.0">1912</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
noted that the 
<typeStatus box="[739,787,907,931]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">type</typeStatus>
specimen is probably from Blumenau. He also stated that 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[151,307,942,967]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catharinae">
<emphasis box="[151,307,942,967]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. catharinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected together with 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[648,745,942,967]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[648,745,942,967]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by himself in Teresópolis (Rio de Janeiro), which we find improbable. We examined 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[453,548,979,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batea">
<emphasis box="[453,548,979,1003]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. batea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Julius Röber, 1906" authorityName="Julius Röber" authorityYear="1906" box="[602,755,979,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Blepolenis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catharinae">
<emphasis box="[602,755,979,1003]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">B. catharinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens from the Fruhstorfer Collection currently housed at The Natural History Museum (London), the former was labeled ‘Santa Catarina’ state but the latter had no locality data. Most of the specimens studied here were collected with fruit-baited traps by W. Gonzales at Lagoa do Peri (open areas and “restinga”). This site is located south of Florianópolis, Santa Catarina, and surrounded by 
<quantity metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="m" value="300.0" valueMax="400.0" valueMin="200.0">200–400 m</quantity>
mountains. In this particular series, some specimens have white spots in dorsal forewing cells M 
<number box="[1271,1281,1122,1146]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1.0">1</number>
and M 
<number box="[1363,1375,1122,1146]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="3.0">3</number>
(
